[src:pino-logging/api-console] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The **`console`** object provides access to the debugging console (e.g., the Web console in Firefox).
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Implementations of the console API may differ between runtimes.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] In particular, some console methods may work differently or not work at all in some online editors and IDEs.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To see the behavior described in this documentation, try the methods in your browser's developer tools, although even here, there are some differences between browsers.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The `console` object is available in any global scope.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Log an error message to console if the first argument is `false`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Log the number of times this line has been called with the given label.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Resets the value of the counter with the given label.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the debug log level.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Displays an interactive listing of the properties of a specified JavaScript object.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] This listing lets you use disclosure triangles to examine the contents of child objects.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Displays an XML/HTML Element representation of the specified object if possible or the JavaScript Object view if it is not possible.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the error log level.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Creates a new inline group, indenting all following output by another level.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To move back out a level, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] However, unlike `console.group()` this starts with the inline group collapsed requiring the use of a disclosure button to expand it.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the info log level.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Starts the browser's built-in profiler (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:pino-logging/api-console] You can specify an optional name for the profile.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] You can see the resulting profile in the browser's performance tool (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Starts a timer with a name specified as an input parameter.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Up to 10,000 simultaneous timers can run on a given page.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Stops the specified timer and logs the elapsed time in milliseconds since it started.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Logs the value of the specified timer to the console.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Adds a marker to the browser performance tool's timeline (Chrome or Firefox).
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the warning log level.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The console's most frequently used feature is logging text and other data.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] There are several categories of output you can generate using the `console.log()`, `console.info()`, `console.warn()`, `console.error()`, or `console.debug()` methods.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Each of these results in output styled differently in the log, and you can use the filtering controls provided by your browser to view only the kinds of output that interest you.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The browser will display as much information about the object as it can and wishes to.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] For example, private state of the object may be displayed too.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Certain types of objects, such as DOM elements or functions, may also be displayed in a special way.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Information about an object is lazily retrieved.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] This means that the log message shows the content of an object at the time when it's first viewed, not when it was logged.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] However, if you expand the object's details, you will see `prop: 123`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] If you are going to mutate your object and you want to prevent the logged information from being updated, you can deep-clone the object before logging it.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] There are other alternatives that work in browsers, such as `structuredClone()`, which are more effective at cloning different types of objects.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The first parameter to the logging methods can be a string containing zero or more substitution strings.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Each substitution string is replaced by the corresponding argument value.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "optimally useful formatting" style, for example DOM elements may be displayed the same way as they would appear in the element inspector.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "generic JavaScript object formatting" style, usually in the form of an expandable tree.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Applies CSS style rules to all following text.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Some browsers may implement additional format specifiers.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] For example, Safari and Firefox support the C-style precision formatting `%.<precision>f`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] For example `console.log("Foo %.2f", 1.1)` will output the number to 2 decimal places: `Foo 1.10`, while `console.log("Foo %.2d", 1.1)` will output the number as two significant figures with a leading 0: `Foo 01`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Each of these pulls the next argument after the format string off the parameter list.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The text before the directive will not be affected, but the text after the directive will be styled using the CSS declarations in the parameter.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] You can use nested groups to help organize your output by visually combining related material.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To create a new nested block, call `console.group()`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The `console.groupCollapsed()` method is similar but creates the new block collapsed, requiring the use of a disclosure button to open it for reading.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To exit the current group, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] You can start a timer to calculate the duration of a specific operation.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To start one, call the `console.time()` method, giving it a name as the only parameter.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] To stop the timer, and to get the elapsed time in milliseconds, just call the `console.timeEnd()` method, again passing the timer's name as the parameter.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Up to 10,000 timers can run simultaneously on a given page.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] Notice that the timer's name is displayed both when the timer is started and when it's stopped.
[src:pino-logging/api-console] The console object also supports outputting a stack trace; this will show you the call path taken to reach the point at which you call `console.trace()`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The **`JSON`** namespace object contains static methods for parsing values from and converting values to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Unlike most global objects, `JSON` is not a constructor.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `JSON` object as a function.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] All properties and methods of `JSON` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] JSON is a syntax for serializing objects, arrays, numbers, strings, booleans, and `null`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] It is based upon JavaScript syntax, but is distinct from JavaScript: most of JavaScript is *not* JSON.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Property names must be double-quoted strings; trailing commas are forbidden.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] A decimal point must be followed by at least one digit.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Any JSON text is a valid JavaScript expression, but only after the JSON superset revision.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Before the revision, U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR are allowed in string literals and property keys in JSON; but the same use in JavaScript string literals is a `SyntaxError`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Other differences include allowing only double-quoted strings and no support for `undefined` or comments.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] For those who wish to use a more human-friendly configuration format based on JSON, there is JSON5, used by the Babel compiler, and the more commonly used YAML.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The same text may represent different values in JavaScript object literals vs.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] For more information, see Object literal syntax vs.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Insignificant whitespace may be present anywhere except within a `JSONNumber` (numbers must contain no whitespace) or `JSONString` (where it is interpreted as the corresponding character in the string, or would cause an error).
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The tab (U+0009), carriage return (U+000D), line feed (U+000A), and space (U+0020) characters are the only valid whitespace characters.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"JSON"`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Tests whether a value is an object returned by `JSON.rawJSON()`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Parse a piece of string text as JSON, optionally transforming the produced value and its properties, and return the value.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Creates a "raw JSON" object containing a piece of JSON text.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] When serialized to JSON, the raw JSON object is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Return a JSON string corresponding to the specified value, optionally including only certain properties or replacing property values in a user-defined manner.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] JSON can contain number literals of arbitrary precision.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] However, it is not possible to represent all JSON numbers exactly in JavaScript, because JavaScript uses floating point representation which has a fixed precision.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] This means there is no JavaScript number that corresponds precisely to the `12345678901234567890` JSON number.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] You want to serialize it and then parse to the same exact number.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] There are, in general, two ways to ensure that numbers are losslessly converted to JSON and parsed back: one involves a JSON number, another involves a JSON string.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] JSON is a *communication format*, so if you use JSON, you are likely communicating with another system (HTTP request, storing in database, etc.).
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The best solution to choose depends on the recipient system.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] If the recipient system does not have same JSON-handling capabilities as JavaScript, and does not support high precision numbers, you may want to serialize the number as a string, and then handle it as a string on the recipient side.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] This is also the only option in older JavaScript.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] To specify how custom data types (including `BigInt`) should be serialized to JSON, either add a `toJSON` method to your data type, or use the `replacer` function of `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] In either case, the JSON text will look like `{"gross_gdp":"12345678901234567890"}`, where the value is a string, not a number.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] Then, on the recipient side, you can parse the JSON and handle the string.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] If the recipient of this message natively supports high precision numbers (such as Python integers), passing numbers as JSON numbers is obviously better, because they can directly parse to the high precision type instead of parsing a string from JSON, and then parsing a number from the string.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] In JavaScript, you can serialize arbitrary data types to JSON numbers without producing a number value first (resulting in loss of precision) by using `JSON.rawJSON()` to precisely specify what the JSON source text should be.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] The text passed to `JSON.rawJSON` is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON, so it won't be serialized again as a string.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] This JSON can then be parsed by the recipient without any extra processing, provided that the recipient system does not have the same precision limitations as JavaScript.
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] When parsing JSON containing high-precision numbers in JavaScript, take extra care because when `JSON.parse()` invokes the `reviver` function, the value you receive is already parsed (and has lost precision).
[src:pino-logging/global-objects-json] You can use the `context.source` parameter of the `JSON.parse()` `reviver` function to re-parse the number yourself.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:pino-logging/logging-computing] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Pino works on Bare with the `pino-bare` compatibility module.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Pino works on Pear, which is built on Bare, with the `pino-bare` compatibility module.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] If you would like to install pino v6, refer to https://github.com/pinojs/pino/tree/v6.x.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Due to Node's single-threaded event-loop, it's highly recommended that sending, alert triggering, reformatting, and all forms of log processing are conducted in a separate process or thread.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] In Pino terminology, we call all log processors "transports" and recommend that the transports be run in a worker thread using our `pino.transport` API.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] For more details see our Transports⇗ document.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Using minimum resources for logging is very important.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Log messages tend to get added over time and this can lead to a throttling effect on applications – such as reduced requests per second.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] In many cases, Pino is over 5x faster than alternatives.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] See the Benchmarks document for comparisons.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Pino supports being bundled using tools like webpack or esbuild.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] See Bundling document for more information.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Pino is an **OPEN Open Source Project**.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] See the CONTRIBUTING.md file for more details.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] This project was kindly sponsored by nearForm.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] This project is kindly sponsored by Platformatic.
[src:pino-logging/pinojs-pino] Logo and identity designed by Cosmic Fox Design: https://www.behance.net/cosmicfox.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:pino-logging/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:pino-logging/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:pino-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
